"/> I'm with you, Judith. I'd prefer not to make offers either on things which I'm
not familiar -- it is often counterproductive and frankly, it makes me
uncomfortable. But occasionally I've been in situations where it has worked to
my advantage when I know the merchandise and I know that the seller doesn't
care much about it. What I do is offer a lowball number and judge their
reaction. In many casees, they take the offer. If they demur, I just then say,
&quot;Well, you gotta give me SOME kind of idea about what you want,&quot; and if they
don't, then I just walk away. Of course all of this depends upon how desirable
the merchandise is. But at least it can start the negotiation ball rolling.

Example: once I was shown a closetful of great vintage clothing at an estate
sale and asked to make an offer on the whole lot. I said, &quot;I dunno, how's $50
for it all?&quot; and they took it -- I eventually cleared more than $1000 on the
clothing (though it took a lot of time and effort.)

A dealer friend of mine taught me to not feel bad about going in with a
lowball number. He said that they often take it (he's right) and it helps at
least put a stake in the ground upon which to base negotiation.

Nancy

