"/> Whether one goes to an auction in person, makes one bid (or most times),
several bids or else leaves a bid with the auctioneer or even bids on the
telephone or GOD forbid on the internet, either way or anyways, one is
making &quot;an offer&quot; Maybe you would like to check the meaning of 'bid' ? Most
times, one is not even aware as to what to auctioneer or the owner will
'really' sell the lot for, or if it's reserved, or the pre-sale estimate is
something of a 'vision' the auctioneer had the previous night in bed, or
indeed, one may very well end-up bidding ONLY against the auctioneer.

....... yes, it is most ridiculous to get into a bidding war at auction,
as it is, just as ridiculous, not to ask the price of something, only,
because it doesn't have a price tag attached to it. Any dealer worth
his/her salt should know what they wish to pay (pre-determined) for any
item or any lot that's on offer, of course the trick and the BIG bonus is,
to 'hopefully' get it for less than one is 'really' prepared to pay.

That may not be always possible, but if you don't try (haggle, bid or
offer) then you can't win. Likewise, if you are at auction and a lot is
being knocked down for a 100 when you KNOW its market value could be around
1000, what are you going to do, stand there like a dummy? Let the other guy
get it for a 100 or even 800, when you can bid, maybe get it and make a few
bob or add it to your collection?

I buy a lot of stuff privately, direct from the normal person in the
street, some of these folk may be factory workers, some may be electricians
and other may be university professors, all may well be experts in their
own job or profession, but most times, they are NOT, antiques dealers and a
lot of times don't HONESTLY know what to ask for the item. They may not ask
a price in fear of asking, too much, and scaring the dealer off, they of
course don't ask a price in-case they ask, too little, and the dealer would
have paid more, we all know that, it isn't some mystical secret. Therefore,
I will do exactly what I do at auction or in some other dealer's shop,
doesn't matter if the item is priced or it is not priced - I &quot;BID&quot; them.
With my &quot;best&quot; offer, slightly below my top price of course, the price I
have &quot;pre-determined&quot; that I 'personally' wish to pay. If they accept my
offer well and good, if we haggle a bit that's OK and in fact, if we do
HAGGLE that will kind a brighten my day quite a bit, after all, I'm, a
dealer :) At the end of the day, if they don't take my offer, then I walk
away, no hard feeling no big loss. It's much the same if they DO ask me a
price, that price could be too high, or a little too high, or maybe just
right either way, I doubt very much I'm going to be giving them the FIRST
price that comes out their mouth.

I don't think we should say &quot;never&quot; look what happen to Sean Connery, and I
certainly don't think one should cut off one nose to spite one face. The
day you buy is the day you sell. :)

