Ok, I've read all these threads and I think I've learned the following:
As a dealer, we don't make an offer to buy something because &quot;maybe&quot; the
person really doesn't want to sell it and we would end up just giving a
free appraisal.
We don't make an offer because maybe the person selling will take their
item to someone else who gives them more.
We don't make an offer because maybe we could have gotten the item for
practically nothing because the poor dummy trying to sell it didn't know
what it was worth.
I guess I'm the dummy because I always felt if someone offered to sell
me something I would tell them what I could pay for it and still make
the profit that I felt necessary to continue on in business. If they
decided to take it somewhere else, so what. I have lost nothing and in
many cases have ended up with a nice item to sell. Granted I never
ended up with $1000.00 worth of merchandise for $50.00, but I still did
just fine. The one thing I did do on occasion was tell the seller that
my offer was only good at that time, not later and I'm sure in some
cases this encouraged them to sell to me rather than take a chance and
shop around.

