A couple of sundays ago, I went with my friend to the flea market to look
for bargains, antiques and whatnot. We took along her seven year old son.
Many of the tables there are junk tables, filled with cheap toys and bric a
brac and occasionally something worthwhile. Well of course, the seven year old
immediately zoomed in on the toys at every table and then came upon a spinning
top (or do all tops spin, I don't know), a piece of plastic junk really, that
he absoluteley had to have.

My friend asked the dealer how much they were and was told they were
$1.00. She decided to wait just a little while, having every intention of
getting him &quot;something&quot; with the idea in mind that he might see something he
liked better.

About an hour passed and all we were hearing was about this wonderful top
and he would not stop so we went back to the booth to buy it for him. When my
friend went to pay the dollar, the gentleman that had quoted the price turned
to a young girl who in turn went in search of her mother. When she came back
she said something to him and he told us that the top was going to be $2.00.
Did the price go up because she was actually going to buy it with real money
showing? I politely told him that he had quoted us $1.00 earlier. &quot;I just
work here&quot; was his response. (I have heard this before, but didn't think
people actually &quot;said&quot; it.)

Needless to say, we walked away and later found the identical item. She
ended up paying $1.50 and the child broke the toy before we left.

Anyway, this is just one example. There are a lot of dealers there who are
more than fair and I have been bringing home items at quite reasonable prices
and then seeing them auctioned off and selling at about a 200% mark-up on
E-bay.

Bottom line, I don't try and cheat them and I think it's pretty obvious
when they are trying to cheat me so I can choose to do business with them or
not. There are all sorts of people in this world, dealers among them, and one
has to treat each person and each situation accordingly. To lump all sellers
or all buyers into any one catagory does not do the good people justice. But
to be fair to everyone (unless provoked into battle) has its rewards. What
goes around does come around; it just takes so damn long sometimes.
Carole.

Reply
</POST>



