I have been trying to stay out of this thread, since everyone has gotten so
emotional, but my self-control has ebbed so here I am commenting too.

I consider myself a collector and I suspect there are many others like me who
are in this newsgroup, learning from the more experienced, including the
dealers. I buy things I like and display them at my home. When I first
started, I bought less expensive things, and sometimes things that were in less
than perfect condition. As time has passed, I have collected more and space
has become a constraint. (How many cream and sugar sets does one have room for
after all?) Also, sometimes I have found things I wanted in box lots at
auctions with other items, leaving me with 12-15 other items in the box lot
that I didn't want plus the fewer things I did want.

So, on 2-3 occasions a few years ago, I shared a booth at a flea market with a
friend to sell off some of the things at the lower end of my collection (e.g.,
damaged items I had replaced with better examples) and things I didn't want.
That didn't disrupt my collection, it improved it. On occasion, some of my
selling prices were as low (and in at least one case lower) than what I had
paid, since I was chiefly trying to get rid of stuff. But I will confess to
making a profit on a couple of items, and don't feel bad about it either.

Having thus given you enough background about me to avoid the condemnation of
dealers that pervades this thread, I must say that I respectfully disagree with
that attack. I do feel wistful when I see things I like priced high by
dealers. And I am as appalled at the Beanie Baby racket as anyone.

But I also recognize that I do not have time to go from estate sale to garage
sale to flea market all the time as I once did, and if it weren't for dealers
scouting for things, I would be able to buy even fewer of the things I like.
So antique dealers make a profit ... that's what capitalism is all about. I
am thankful for the dealers who shop garage sales in California or wherever,
and puts items on ebay so that I can buy them from my computer in NY. I
wouldn't get them otherwise.

And, by creating a larger market for antiques, dealers create an incentive for
people to safeguard rather than destroy their old things. After all, what is
treasure to someone may be junk to someone else. Especially for, say, paper
items (old advertising, letters, postcards, or whatever else people collect),
without a market-based incentive to value those things, the owners may just
toss the stuff in the garbage, destroying it forever. There won't necessarily
be a true collector of any given item at any given garage sale.

Well, I know I won't have persuaded Dr. Bellows, but at least I've gotten this
off my chest. But Dr. Bellows, don't flee the newsgroup. We need all sorts of
folks here, and I for one don't consider you a troll, just someone with very
strong divergent opinions.

